EXT. PARK BENCH - SUNRISE
A man, MAN, is sitting on a bench. A notepad lies on his lap. He is ignoring the sunrise. He takes a deep breath and picks up his pen, ready to write.

MAN (v.o.)
Chère Maman... Tu me manques. (Dear Mom... I miss you.)

MAN softly shakes his head and scratches out the words. He takes another soft breath and starts writing again.

MAN (v.o.)
Chère Maman... J'ai commencé à réfléchir au progrès... Je repensais à notre dernière conversation... Et cela m'a rappelé notre voyage en train de Toulouse à... je ne sais plus où... (Dear Mom... I have started thinking about progress... I was thinking about our last conversation... And it reminded me of our train ride from Toulouse to... I can't remember where...)

MAN softly shakes his head again and scratches out the words. He takes another soft breath and starts writing again.

MAN (v.o.)
Maman... Je repensais à notre dernière conversation... Que voulais-tu dire quand tu as dit : « (Mom... I was thinking about our last conversation... What did you mean when you said, " )

WOMAN (o.s.)
Appeler...

MAN does not notice/acknowledge the voice. He continues writing.

MAN
(Beckon sentence in English)

WOMAN (o.s.)
Appeler...

MAN slowly looks around at Nature, searching for the source. Is it his mother? The wind? He goes back to writing.

MAN
(Beckon sentence in English)

WOMAN (o.s.)
Appeler...

MAN remembers the word. He begins writing.

A WOMAN, 30s, is sitting on a parallel bench across the lookout.

MAN (v.o.)
(Says the BECKON sentence in French)

WOMAN
(softly)
Come here often?

MAN
(surprised)
Huh?

WOMAN
(louder)
Do you come here often?

MAN
Ah... yes. In the mornings, you?

WOMAN
(smiles)
Wouldn't you know if you come here often?

MAN
(smiles back)
Not with certainty.

WOMAN 
(pauses)
Passing through. Duluth. Keokuck. Now... As good a stop as any, wouldn't you say?

MAN
Why?

WOMAN gestures for him to look at the landscape with her eyes. 

MAN
Why are you passing through?

WOMAN prepares for a big anecdote.

MAN
(cuts her off)
What are you reading?

WOMAN
Oh, Pushkin.

She holds up the book for him to see. It's a worn copy of Eugene Onegin.

MAN
In Russian?

WOMAN
No, translation.

MAN
Oh.

MAN returns to his notebook. WOMAN slowly pulls out a folded map.

 WOMAN
Would you happen to know the way out?

MAN
Straight down. Take a right at the sycamore by the bend. Then you'll hit the main road.

WOMAN
What does a sycamore look like? 

MAN
If you have gone too far, you'll know.

MAN closes his notebook, stands up. He takes a few steps forward, then lights a cigarette. 

WOMAN folds up her map and returns to her book.

WOMAN
(while reading)
It's not all translatable, you know. But how else would we know of Pushkin?

MAN
(defeated)
Hmm... Feeble meaning is still better than nothing at all. 

Gust of wind blows through the trees. MAN and WOMAN are taken by surprise. 

WOMAN
Is it a poem? 

MAN
Something like that. (Laughs) It doesn't rhyme. 





